Money Stuff =0A If you are a shareholder of a public company, how would you=
 like that company =0Ato be run=3F Here are two options: The chief executiv=
e officer o =0A=0A=0A <> =0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D8258=
81&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12500861&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D02=
032025>=0A=0A=0A=0AMeta to Texas=0A=0AIf you are a shareholder of a public =
company, how would you like that company =0Ato be run=3F Here are two optio=
ns:=0A=0A * The chief executive officer of the company has to run the compa=
ny in the =0Ainterests of shareholders. There are rules in place to avoid e=
ven the =0Aappearance of a conflict of interest. If she takes the company j=
et to a morning =0Abusiness meeting and then spends the afternoon sightseei=
ng, she has to =0Areimburse the company for a ratable portion of the fuel s=
he used. If she wants =0Ato acquire another company whose assistant treasur=
er=E2=80=99s nephew once played on a =0ALittle League team with her first c=
ousin once removed, the board of directors =0Awill have to set up a special=
 committee to review the deal, and she will have =0Ato recuse herself from =
decisions about price to avoid the risk of personal =0Afavoritism. =0A * Th=
e chief executive officer of the company can do whatever he wants. He can =
