ty, or at =0Aleast in casinos, to pay for goods and services.=0A=0A=0APredi=
ction markets=0A=0AMy Fifth Law of Insider Trading <> is: Don=E2=80=99t ins=
ider trade by planting bombs =0Aat a company <> and shorting its stock. (Th=
ese laws are not legal advice, but =0Ahonestly I strongly recommend that yo=
u follow that one.) This is a law of =0Ainsider trading because =E2=80=A6 i=
t could work=3F This is a real temptation=3F The law was =0Aoriginally insp=
ired by someone who allegedly did it, shorting the stock of =0ABorussia Dor=
tmund GmBH, the soccer team, and thenplanting bombs <> by the route =0Aof t=
he team bus. And we have talked about other speculative applications =0Ainc=
ludinghacking <> (hack a company, short its stock, announce the hack), =0At=
errorism <> (there was supposedly some short selling of Israeli stocks befo=
re =0Athe Oct. 7 Hamas attacks), ormedical-device sabotage <> (hack a pacem=
aker, =0Ashort the manufacturer=E2=80=99s stock, kill some patients). Again=
,don=E2=80=99t do these =0Athings.=0A=0AIn each case, what you are doing is=
 arguably insider trading or market =0Amanipulation, [8]  <> but it is also=
 separately some other crime: If you hack =0Apacemakers to kill people to p=
rofit from a short position on a medical device =0Amanufacturer, the troubl=
e you will get in for insider trading is not nearly as =0Abad as the troubl=
e you will get in for murder. Still, I regularly say around =0Ahere that =
=E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud <>,=E2=80=9D and that securities re=
gulation =0Ais a form ofmeta-regulation <> that covers every sort of bad ac=
t, so I suppose =0Aone day someone will do a murder and be prosecuted for s=
ecurities fraud. =0A=E2=80=9CLadies and gentlemen of the jury, the defendan=
t undermined the integrity of =0Asecurities markets by killing all those pe=
ople.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AIn the stock market, insider trading is frowned upon. I=
n prediction markets, =0Athings are more nuanced: A lot of prediction-marke=
t theorists and advocates and =0Aexecutiveslike insider trading <>, because=
 the social purpose of a prediction =0Amarket is to make good predictions, =
and insiders might have better information =0A=E2=80=94 and so make better =
predictions =E2=80=94 than outsiders. [9]  <> You, uh, see where =0Athis is=
 going.=0A=0APrediction markets these days are still pretty small, so there=
 is not a ton of =0Atemptation to buy a =E2=80=9Cterrorism will happen=E2=
=80=9D event contract and then do =0Aterrorism for profit. But I am mention=
ing it here because (1) there=E2=80=99s aWall =0AStreet Journal article <> =
about prediction markets on California wildfires and =0A(2) as prediction m=
arkets get bigger and more mainstream, perhaps we will have =0Aoccasion to =
revisit this point. From the Journal:=0A=0AIn January, as deadly wildfires =
ripped through Los Angeles, Polymarket allowed =0Ausers to bet on when the =
Palisades fire would be fully contained, whether it =0Awould spread to Sant=
a Monica within a given time, and other questions about the =0Adisaster.=0A=
=0AA columnist for the Los Angeles Times slammed the wildfire contracts as =
=0Aghoulish. Another observer=E2=80=94Molly White, an independent researche=
r who studies =0Athe crypto industry=E2=80=94argued that the contracts coul=
d encourage bettors to engage =0Ain arson for profit.=0A=0A=E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s a grim reflection of society that there are people who see a wildfi=
re =0Aand decide that they should try and make money on it,=E2=80=9D White =
said.=0A=0AYeah I mean that=E2=80=99s more of a critique of society than it=
 is of prediction =0Amarkets. Also: There are famously already ways to enga=
ge in arson for profit, =0Aand there are laws against it that don=E2=80=99t=
 involve prediction market regulation. =0A(Arson is a crime!) But, yes, pre=
diction markets offer the possibility of more =0Acomplete markets: Whatever=
 future event you might want to bet on, you can =0Aimagine a contract for i=
t. And then you might be tempted to make the event =0Ahappen.=0A=0A=0AThing=
s happen=0A=0AVanguard=E2=80=99s Average Fee Is Now Just 0.07% After Bigges=
t-Ever Cut <>. Corporate =0AAmericacosies up to Elon Musk <> as billionaire=
 deepens ties to Donald Trump. =0AMusk Says DOGEHalting Treasury Payments <=
> to US Contractors. Musk=E2=80=99s X Adds =0ANestl=C3=A9, Colgate, Shell, =
Other Brands toAd-Boycott Suit <>. =E2=80=9CExpensive nuclear =0Aplants fin=
anced in complicated ways offer a convenient way toconceal money <> =0Amovi=
ng for other reasons.=E2=80=9D OpenAI Releases AI Agent Designed to Act Lik=
e a=0AResearch Analyst <>. Samsung chair cleared of fraud <> and stock mani=
pulation. =0AAfter Banker Dies,Jefferies <> Vows Support and Slams Online V=
enom. Sam =0ABankman-Fried=E2=80=99s Parents ExploreSeeking Trump Pardon <>=
 for Son. =E2=80=9CIt is a funny =0Asort of nihilism thatbelieves in nothin=
g except belief itself <>.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AIf you'd like to get Money Stuff i=
n handy email form, right in your inbox, =0Apleasesubscribe at this link <>=
. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other =0Agreat Bloomberg newslet=
tershere <>. Thanks!=0A=0A[1] You could check the box at the time of incorp=
oration. If you wanted to do =0Ait later, after you already have outside sh=
areholders, there=E2=80=99d have to be a =0Ashareholder vote and a series o=
f vicious lawsuits. It=E2=80=99s still Delaware.=0A=0A[2] Actually a lot of=
 it is in the form of canceling (at par) $631 million of =0Aexisting interc=
ompany debt (see page 20 ofthe prospectus <>), but I assume that =0Athat de=
bt was incurred mostly in exchange for Bally=E2=80=99s actually paying the =
costs =0Aof development, so ultimately for Bally=E2=80=99s cash. Also to be=
 fair a lot of the =0Acash is a =E2=80=9CPost-IPO Capital Commitment by Bal=
ly=E2=80=99s Chicago HoldCo to provide to =0ABally=E2=80=99s Chicago OpCo u=
p to $369.0 million in additional funding" (page 167), so =0Anot cash *now*=
, but still.=0A=0A[3] Not *too* much. See pages 166 to 169 of the prospectu=
s <> on related party =0Atransactions. My point here is that if Bally=E2=80=
=99s loaned the Chicago casino entity =0A$500 million at 30% interest, and =
then had 75% of the equity, the loan =0Aeconomics would sort of swamp its (=
and the public=E2=80=99s) equity interests. But =0Athat=E2=80=99s not true =
here. There is a subordinated note for the $250 discounted =0Ashares sold t=
o some investors, and that does swamp *their* equity, but it=E2=80=99s a =
=0Afairly small fraction of the equity. There are also some management cont=
racts =0Awith Bally=E2=80=99s (page 166), a temporary one for $5 million a =
month until the =0Acasino is up and running, and a permanent one for =E2=80=
=9Cgeneral business support =0Aservices=E2=80=9D at cost plus 6%. So Bally=
=E2=80=99s certainly has some economics that are =0Asenior to the equity, b=
ut from reading the prospectus they don=E2=80=99t seem all that =0Aextreme.=
=0A=0A[4] That=E2=80=99s from Bloomberg page BALY US Equity FA EV. In Octob=
er, Bally=E2=80=99s =0Aestimated <> =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D of $5=
55 million in 2024, $615 million in 2025 =0Aand $699 million in 2026.=0A=0A=
[5] In its most recent report <> of share sales, it reported 281.7 million =
=0Adiluted shares outstanding and 245.8 million basic shares as of Jan. 26.=
 Using =0Athe diluted shares and today=E2=80=99s price of around $333 per s=
hare, you get a market =0Acap of $96 billion. (That=E2=80=99s not the right=
 math =E2=80=94 you=E2=80=99d want to use the treasury =0Astock method for =
the convertibles and options, which would get you a somewhat =0Alower numbe=
r =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s close enough; the basic market cap is $84 bill=
ion.) =0ASince then it has sold some convertible preferred stock, so a slig=
htly higher =0Adiluted market cap.=0A=0A[6] It has, again, $47 billion of *=
Bitcoin* on hand, but selling that to pay =0Adividends would defeat the who=
le purpose of all of this.=0A=0A[7] Maybe  AI can be <>=3F=3F=3F=0A=0A[8] A=
rguably it isn=E2=80=99t=3F You=E2=80=99re trading on your own (bad) intent=
ions=3F And you =0Aare not manipulating *the market*; you=E2=80=99re manipu=
lating reality=3F Still. I feel =0Alike if you did this and got caught, the=
 US Securities and Exchange Commission =0Awould come after you for some sor=
t of securities fraud theory.=0A=0A[9] *One* social purpose of a stock mark=
et is to produce accurate valuations =0Aof stocks, but there are others =E2=
=80=94 to let people save for retirement, for =0Ainstance =E2=80=94 that cu=
t against insider trading. But a lot of people think insider =0Atrading sho=
uld be legal in stock markets too, to make prices more efficient.=0A=0A=0A =
